<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><rss xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:content="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" version="2.0"><channel><title><![CDATA[@rathod-sahaab's blog]]></title><description><![CDATA[Sharing what I learn to help others and future me :)]]></description><link>https://rathod-sahaab.github.io/blog</link><generator>GatsbyJS</generator><lastBuildDate>Wed, 02 Jun 2021 05:15:06 GMT</lastBuildDate><item><title><![CDATA[Accelerating libnbd on linux using io_uring [0]]]></title><description><![CDATA[io_uring is the new and better way to do asynchronus I/O on linux, tag along with me on a journey to learning of doing on a real life project libnbd!]]></description><link>https://rathod-sahaab.github.io/blog/posts/libnbd-io_uring-0</link><guid isPermaLink="false">https://rathod-sahaab.github.io/blog/posts/libnbd-io_uring-0</guid><pubDate>Mon, 24 May 2021 06:31:00 GMT</pubDate><content:encoded>&lt;h2 id=&quot;background&quot; style=&quot;position:relative;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;#background&quot; aria-label=&quot;background permalink&quot; class=&quot;anchor before&quot;&gt;&lt;svg aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; focusable=&quot;false&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; version=&quot;1.1&quot; viewBox=&quot;0 0 16 16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot;&gt;&lt;path fill-rule=&quot;evenodd&quot; d=&quot;M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z&quot;&gt;&lt;/path&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Background&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I was learning about operating systems and got interested in systems programming, I was casually browsing through GSoC 2020 projects to look for an interesting one (which is a pretty good way to find projects). I was immediately taken by the &lt;em&gt;libnbd / nbdcopy accleration using io&lt;/em&gt;_&lt;em&gt;uring&lt;/em&gt; on &lt;a href=&quot;https://wiki.libvirt.org/page/Google_Summer_of_Code_Ideas&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener noreferrer&quot;&gt;libvirt’s GSoC page&lt;/a&gt;. I immediately pinged Richard about if the project was up for taking, it was. So, I started learning and planning for the project and Thanks to Richard’s guidance the process was much easier.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As my college requires some kind of internship after 6th sem, I applied for GSoC and my proposal was selected for Google Summer of Code. Officially, coding begins on 7 June 2021 but I have began testing waters for this daunting task already.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&quot;motivation&quot; style=&quot;position:relative;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;#motivation&quot; aria-label=&quot;motivation permalink&quot; class=&quot;anchor before&quot;&gt;&lt;svg aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; focusable=&quot;false&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; version=&quot;1.1&quot; viewBox=&quot;0 0 16 16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot;&gt;&lt;path fill-rule=&quot;evenodd&quot; d=&quot;M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z&quot;&gt;&lt;/path&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Motivation&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Using io_uring would improve efficiency and thoroughput hence better performance for programs that us libnbd.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&quot;io_uring&quot; style=&quot;position:relative;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;#io_uring&quot; aria-label=&quot;io_uring permalink&quot; class=&quot;anchor before&quot;&gt;&lt;svg aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; focusable=&quot;false&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; version=&quot;1.1&quot; viewBox=&quot;0 0 16 16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot;&gt;&lt;path fill-rule=&quot;evenodd&quot; d=&quot;M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z&quot;&gt;&lt;/path&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;&lt;/a&gt;io_uring&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Though there are already many ways to do async I/O on linux but io_uring is faster because of following reasons:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;No locks on the shared data between kernel and process.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Ability to submit multiple I/O request in one &lt;em&gt;syscall&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://kernel.dk/io_uring.pdf&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener noreferrer&quot;&gt;Official Paper on io_uring&lt;/a&gt; by Jens Axboe goes in much more details, so make sure to give this masterpiece a read. The best practice it to &lt;strong&gt;NOT&lt;/strong&gt; use io&lt;em&gt;uring but &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/axboe/liburing&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener noreferrer&quot;&gt;liburing&lt;/a&gt; a library made to simplify using io&lt;/em&gt;uring.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&quot;libnbd&quot; style=&quot;position:relative;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;#libnbd&quot; aria-label=&quot;libnbd permalink&quot; class=&quot;anchor before&quot;&gt;&lt;svg aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; focusable=&quot;false&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; version=&quot;1.1&quot; viewBox=&quot;0 0 16 16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot;&gt;&lt;path fill-rule=&quot;evenodd&quot; d=&quot;M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z&quot;&gt;&lt;/path&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;&lt;/a&gt;libnbd&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It is a NBD client library in userspace. The library is hosted at &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/libguestfs/libnbd&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener noreferrer&quot;&gt;libguestfs/libnbd&lt;/a&gt;. It enables programmers to read from and right to block-devices programatically.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&quot;network-block-device&quot; style=&quot;position:relative;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;#network-block-device&quot; aria-label=&quot;network block device permalink&quot; class=&quot;anchor before&quot;&gt;&lt;svg aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; focusable=&quot;false&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; version=&quot;1.1&quot; viewBox=&quot;0 0 16 16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot;&gt;&lt;path fill-rule=&quot;evenodd&quot; d=&quot;M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z&quot;&gt;&lt;/path&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Network Block Device&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;NBD — Network Block Device — is a protocol for accessing Block Devices
(hard disks and disk-like things) over a Network. This is the NBD
client library in userspace, a simple library for writing NBD clients.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Basic idea reading and writing blocks of binary data over the network.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&quot;future-posts&quot; style=&quot;position:relative;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;#future-posts&quot; aria-label=&quot;future posts permalink&quot; class=&quot;anchor before&quot;&gt;&lt;svg aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; focusable=&quot;false&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; version=&quot;1.1&quot; viewBox=&quot;0 0 16 16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot;&gt;&lt;path fill-rule=&quot;evenodd&quot; d=&quot;M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z&quot;&gt;&lt;/path&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Future posts&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I will go in details as I go forward with the project via new posts. But that’s it for now. Thanks for tuning in.&lt;/p&gt;</content:encoded></item></channel></rss>